Abstract
In many engineering problems, ranging from earthquake ground motions to acoustic propa-
gation and environmental engineering problems, stochastic analysis involves the modeling of
input parameters that vary randomly in space and/or time (e.g., load distributions or material
parameters). This type of uncertainty can be modeled by means of random elds.
The UQLAB random eld module offers an easy way to dene a random eld, discretize it
for use in engineering problems featuring time/space variability and, eventually, to sample
trajectories from it.
The manual is divided into the following three parts:
A short review of the main methods that are used to dene, discretize and generate a
random eld;
An in-depth, example-driven user guide, with the explanation of most of the available
options and methods;
A comprehensive reference list detailing all the available functionalities in UQLAB.
Keywords: Random eld, Karhunen-Lo
`
eve, EOLE, Probabilistic input model, Sampling.

Chapter 1
Theory
1.1 Introduction
In many engineering elds, statistical analysis can require the modeling of input parame-
ters that vary randomly in space and/or time (e.g., load distributions or material properties).
Random elds (RF) theory is a mathematically rigorous framework that allows for the mod-
elling of this type of uncertainty. Random elds represent random quantities that are dened
over a continuous domain, and thus consist of an innite number of random variables. To
make them computationally treatable, it is therefore necessary to discretize them.
Various discretization methods have been developed in the literature for representing ran-
dom elds in a way that is suitable for a subsequent sampling (Sudret and Der Kiureghian,
2000). Two well-known methods are currently implemented in UQLAB, namely Karhunen-
Lo
`
eve expansion (KLE) (Ghanem and Spanos, 1991) and expansion optimal linear estimation
(EOLE) (Li and Der Kiureghian, 1993). They belong to a class of so-called series expan-
sion methods, where a particular realization of the random eld is represented by a nite
sum of deterministic functions. In KLE and EOLE, these functions are obtained using the
spectral decomposition of the covariance of the random eld (Karhunen, 1947; Spanos and
Ghanem, 1989). These methods are particularly efcient since they capture the variability of
the uncertain quantity using only a small number of random variables, hence reducing the
dimensionality of the problem while preserving, to a given extent, the key statistics of the
considered random eld (Marzouk and Najm, 2009).
In some applications, additional information, such as the exact values of the random eld
at some locations, is available. Such cases are dealt with in the framework of conditional
random elds. Two such techniques are implemented in UQLAB and briey presented in this
report.
1
UQLAB user manual
1.2 Basics of random elds
The theory of random elds is treated in Lin (1967); Vanmarcke and Grigoriu (1983); Van-
marcke et al. (1986). In this section, we describe the basic elements necessary to understand
and use the random eld module of UQLAB.
Let us consider the Hilbert space L
2
(, F, P) of all random variables with nite variance. Let
D R
d
be a domain that describes the geometry of the system. A random eld H(x, ) : D
R is a set of random variables indexed by a continuous parameter x D representing
a coordinate in the topological space D, with being an outcome in the sample space .
The dimension d of a random eld is the dimension of its topological space D. One usu-
ally distinguishes between a one- and a multi-dimensional random eld, depending on the
dimension of x, that is whether d = 1 or d > 1. Furthermore, a random eld is said to be
univariate or real-valued if the random quantity attached to each point x is a random vari-
able. The random eld is multivariate if the random quantity is a random vector. It is worth
to note that the domain is not reserved only to a space domain, it can be any type of domain,
such as a time domain, in which the random eld is usually called stochastic process.
Two main categories of random elds can be dened based on their probability distribution:
Gaussian and non-Gaussian. In this manual, we will only consider Gaussian random elds, as
well as a special class of non-Gaussian ones, the so-called translation non-Gaussian random
elds.
The Gaussian assumption is usually employed for its simplicity. A random eld is said Gaus-
sian if the distribution of H(x

1.3 Discretization of a random eld
The discretization of a random eld H(x, ) is a process by which the random eld is ap-
proximated using a nite set of random variables, making it suitable for computational ap-
plications. The main goal is to dene the best approximation with respect to some error
estimator, that is the one requiring the minimal number of random variables (Sudret and
Der Kiureghian, 2000).
Various techniques have been developed for the discretization of random elds in the litera-
ture, as reviewed in Li and Der Kiureghian (1993); Ditlevsen (1996); Matthies et al. (1997).
They can be divided into three groups (Sudret and Der Kiureghian, 2000):
point discretization: the random eld is described by a set of random variables that
represent the values of the random eld at some given points, such as the mid-point or
the shape function methods;
average discretization: the random variables are averaged over local domains, such as
the weighted integral or the spatial average methods;
series expansion methods: where the random eld is exactly represented as a series in-
volving a complete set of deterministic functions with corresponding random variables,
such as Karhunen-Lo
`
eve.
Only series expansion methods are considered in UQLAB. This manual focuses on the two
methods currently implemented, namely the Karhunen-Lo
`
eve expansion and the expansion
optimal linear estimation.
1.3.1 Karhunen Lo
`

Karhunen-Lo
`

random eld discretization techniques. It is optimal among series expansion methods in
terms of the global mean square error with respect to the number of random variables in
the discretization (Ghanem and Spanos, 1991). In essence, KLE is based on the spectral
expansion of the process covariance function, using orthogonal deterministic basis functions
and uncorrelated random coefcients.

Chapter 2
Usage
In this section, the discretization of a random eld as discussed in Chapter 1 is described.
An example involving a one-dimensional Gaussian random eld is employed to illustrate the
usage of the module.
2.1 Gaussian random elds
2.1.1 Introductory example
As an introductory example, a one-dimensional Gaussian random eld dened on a domain
= [1, 1] is investigated. The random eld is assumed to have a constant mean = 1 and
standard deviation = 1. The correlation function is Gaussian with correlation length 0.2.
The expansion optimal linear estimation (EOLE) is chosen as discretization technique with a
target energy ratio of 0.99.
2.1.2 Problem set-up
The random eld module creates an INPUT object that can be used exactly as any other. The
basic options common to any random eld module read:
uqlab;
RFInput.Type = 'RandomField';
The ingredients selected by the user to describe the random eld are stored in the structure
RFInput. The following elds are mandatory:
RFInput.RFType the type of random eld (e.g. Gaussian or lognormal).
RFInput.Corr.Family correlation family.
RFInput.Corr.Length the correlation length.
11
UQLAB user manual
RFInput.Mean the mean of the random eld.
RFInput.Std the standard deviation of the random eld.
RFInput.Mesh the domain of denition of the random eld and the mesh used when
sampling trajectories.
The remaining parameters are optional and given default values in UQLAB as described in
Table 1.
2.1.3 Creating a random eld object
A minimal conguration example to setup a random eld in UQLAB (Section 2.1.2) is given
in the following block of code.
uqlab;
RFInput.Type = 'RandomField';
RFInput.Corr.Family = 'Gaussian';
RFInput.Corr.Length = 0.2;
RFInput.Mean=1;
RFInput.Std=1;
RFInput.Mesh= linspace(-1,1,200)';
myRF = uq_createInput(RFInput);
Note: The remaining parameters are set by default within the module:
Random eld type (RFInput.Type): Gaussian
Energy ratio threshold (
e
in Eq. (1.11), RFInput.EnergyRatio): 0.99. The
corresponding expansion order is computed using Eq. (1.29).
Discretization scheme (RFInput.DiscScheme): EOLE
Once the random eld is created, a report with basic information about the random eld
results can be printed with the command:
uq_print(myRF);
which, in our example, produces the following output:
------------------- Random Field properties ------------------
Input object name : Input 1
Random field type : Gaussian
Discretization scheme : EOLE
Autocorrelation family : Gaussian
Expansion order : 10
Average error Variance : 4.82e-03
Explained variance : 0.9948

This shows the basic information about the random eld. The average error variance is
computed over the covariance mesh while the explained variance or energy ratio is computed
using Eq. (1.29).
Note: the total number of eigenvalues used to compute the approximate energy ratio
is limited by the mesh grid. The user must therefore make sure that the dis-
cretization mesh used is sufcient to accurately represent the random eld. An
heuristic approach is to assess visually the convergence of the energy ratio using
uq_display (Figure 1b).
A visual representation of the INPUT object can be obtained by:
uq_display(myRF)

one-dimensional problems and a single realization for two-dimenstional problems. The right
panel shows the variance error. Figure 1b shows the eigenvalues resulting from the spectral
decomposition of the auto-correlation matrix.

Underlying standard Gaussian input
The random variables {

random eld are realizations of an M -dimensional independent standard Gaussian distri-

information needed to generate the random trajectories used in many uncertainty quanti-
cation analyses. The corresponding INPUT object that can be used for other analyses within
UQLAB is therefore also returned with the random eld object and can be accessed in the
eld myRF.UnderlyingGaussian.
2.2 Multi-dimensional random elds
It is also possible to generate a multi-dimensional random elds. The size of the mesh or
the correlation length should be adapted accordingly. No additional conguration is needed
to enable this behaviour. For example, a two-dimensional random eld can be specied by
enabling a mesh of size m 2. In UQLAB, this can be specied as follows:
x = linspace(-1,1,50);
y= linspace(-1,1,50);
[X,Y] = meshgrid(x,y);
RFInput.Mesh= [X(:) Y(:)];
One may also dene an anisotropic correlation function by choosing different correlation
lengths per direction. This can be specied as follows:
RFInput.Corr.Length= [0.2, 0.6] ;
Figure 2 displays one realization of a two-dimensional random eld using the settings dened
above. The resulting expansion order is M = 38.
2.3 Drawing samples from a random eld
Samples from the INPUT object myRF are realizations of the random eld on the discretization
mesh. They can be obtained as follows:
X = uq_getSample(300);

where X is a vector of size 300 m, with m being the number of points in the discretization

Notice that we do not need to dene the INPUT object in uq_getSample, because after an

calling uq_getSample. The MATLAB standard random number generator is used by default.
When using uq_getSample in order to obtain samples from a random eld, various sam-

to sample from the INPUT object myRF as follows:
X = uq_getSample(300, 'LHS');

When some vectors and a random eld object myRF are available, it is possible to construct
the random eld trajectories using the function uq_RF_Xi_to_X as follows:
X = uq_RF_Xi_to_X(myRF,xi)

2.4 Set-up of the random eld
2.4.1 Discretization scheme
The default discretization scheme is EOLE. The user may alternatively consider Karhunen-
Lo
`
eve by specifying the following:
RFInput.DiscScheme = 'KL';
There are different solution schemes used within KLE, which may be specied using the
.KL.Method eld. Generally, the Nystr
om method with full quadrature is considered by
default, except when the exponential kernel is used to compute the covariance (in which
case an analytical solution scheme is adopted).
2.4.2 Domain of discretization
The generation of a random eld requires the denition of a set of points (or mesh) where it
will be evaluated. UQLAB provides ways to do it:
Dene the input domain D, through RFInput.Domain, together with the number of
points along each direction RFInput.SPD. This results in a uniform grid over the input
domain. RFInput.Domain is a 2 d vector where the rst and second row represent
the lower and upper bounds of the domain, respectively, and d is the dimension of the
random eld. RFInput.SPD is a scalar in case of one-dimensional random elds. For
multidimensional elds, it may either be a vector with size 1 d or a scalar, in which
case the same value is repeated in all directions.
The following code creates a one-dimensional regular mesh with 200 nodes on D =
[1, 1]:
RFInput.Domain = [-1; 1];
RFInput.SPD = 200;
Alternatively, one may directly provide the coordinates of the mesh nodes using the
.Mesh, eld as shown in Section 2.1.3. RFInput.Mesh is a matrix of size m d, where
m is the number of nodes in the mesh.
UQLAB-V2.0-119 - 17 -
UQLAB user manual
2.4.3 Covariance mesh
The mesh dened using the options described in Section 2.4.2 is used for sampling the ran-
dom eld. To actually perform the spectral decomposition of the covariance, however, a
different mesh is used in general. The actual mesh depends on the discretization method
considered and the properties of the eld. In some cases, this mesh is entirely determined by
the method and cannot be modied by the user.
Note: For both KL and EOLE, it is recommended to use a non-regular grid only for
problems of dimension larger than 2.
Karhunen-Lo

Nystr

specify the quadrature type and the number of nodes. The former can be specied

code may be used:
RFInput.KL.Quadrature = 'Full' ;

Expansion optimal linear estimation (EOLE)
For EOLE, the covariance mesh may be different from the sampling mesh dened in Sec-
tion 2.4.2. By default and for random elds with dimension smaller than 3, it is a regular
grid with 5 samples points are used per correlation length in each direction. For higher-
dimensional random elds, the mesh is generated randomly using Latin hypercube sampling
(LHS).
In case of EOLE, there are many ways to specify the covariance mesh:
The user can directly enter a mesh which is consistent with the dimension of the random
eld using the following option:
RFInput.EOLE.CovMesh = Z;
Here Z is a vector of size n d, where n is the number of points in the mesh. Any
sampling scheme can be used, even a non-regular grid. The user must however make
sure that the number of points is large enough to obtain a good approximation accuracy.
The user may directly enter the number of nodes per correlation length and dimension,
together with a sampling technique. For example, to use 10 points per correlation
length and a regular grid obtained by full tensorization, one may specify:
RFInput.EOLE.SPC = 5 ;
RFInput.EOLE.Sampling = 'grid' ;
In this case, the number of nodes per i-th dimension is given by Eq. (2.1) and the total
number of points in the mesh is n =

the following code produces a 2D mesh with 30 nodes in the rst dimension and 20 in
the second, sampled using LHS:
RFInput.EOLE.SPD = [30 20] ;
RFInput.EOLE.Sampling = 'LHS' ;
In this example, a total of n = 600 = 30 20 samples are drawn uniformly by LHS in
the discretization domain (i.e., without any tensorization).
Finally, the user may directly specify the total number of samples and the sampling
technique. For instance, the user may specify the following to create a mesh containing
n = 1000 uniformly distributed points using LHS:
RFInput.EOLE.NSamples = 1000 ;
RFInput.EOLE.Sampling = 'LHS' ;

2.4.4 Correlation function
The correlation function is dened using the UQLIB library (See UQLIB user manual). Any
kernel available in UQLAB can be used within the random eld module.
The main ingredients for specifying the correlation function are:
Correlation type: separable or ellipsoidal (see UQLIB user manual, Section 2.3.1).
For example, in order to use a separable correlation function the following option is
needed:
RFInput.Corr.Type = 'Separable';
Correlation family: the kernel family (see UQLIB user manual, Section 2.3.1). For
example, in order to use an exponential correlation function the following option is
needed:
RFInput.Corr.Family = 'exponential';
Correlation length: The scaling parameters for the correlation function. It may be a
scalar for one-dimensional and isotropic multi-dimensional cases. For an anisotropic
random eld, the vector must have d elements. As an example, the correlation length
for an anisotropic two-dimensional random eld in may be specied as follows:
RFInput.Corr.Length = [0.3 0.5] ;
For more details about the conguration options available for the correlation function, please
refer to the UQLIB user manual. In Figure 3, various one-dimensional random eld trajecto-
ries are plotted using different correlation families.
2.5 Non-Gaussian translation random elds
The module currently supports only Gaussian random elds and a special class of non-
Gaussian ones, known as translation random elds. Such elds are obtained by iso-
probabilistically transforming Gaussian random elds, such that the marginals at each mesh
point follow a desired non-Gaussian distribution (e.g., lognormal or Gumbel), while the cop-
ula remains Gaussian.
A popular example of such elds is the lognormal random eld, often used to describe pa-
rameters that are constrained to be positive. Such a random eld can be generated in UQLAB
using the following command:
UQLAB-V2.0-119 - 20 -
Random elds
Figure 3: Three random eld trajectories using the Gaussian, exponential and Mat

correlations families.
RFInput.RFType = 'Lognormal';
In general, UQLAB allows setting any marginal that is completely dened by its mean and
variance using the command RFType.
Finally, once a random eld is created, the user can easily transform its realizations into ones
with a different marginal distribution but the same moments by using the helper function:
Y = uq_translateRF(X,RF, TargetDistrib)
where X are realizations of a random eld in from object RF and TargetDistrib is the
desired distribution.
Currently any marginal distribution available in UQLAB (See Section 1.2 of UQLAB User
Manual the INPUT module) and uniquely dened by its moments can be used.
2.6 Conditional random elds
Conguring a conditional random eld is very similar to setting up a Gaussian RF. In this
case, a set of observations, dened as a set of locations at which the random eld values are
known, is needed. The data can be provided through the RFData.X and RFData.Y elds:
RFInput.RFData.X= [-0.5 0 0.5]';
RFInput.RFData.Y = [0.5, 1, 1.5]';

3.2 Getting samples from an INPUT object: uq_getSample
Syntax
X = uq_getSample(N)
X = uq_getSample(myInput,N)
X = uq_getSample(N,method)
X = uq_getSample(myInput,N,method)
X = uq_getSample(N,method,Name,Value)
X = uq_getSample(myInput,N,method,Name,Value)
X = uq_getSample(...)
[X, xi] = uq_getSample(...)
Description
X = uq_getSample(N) returns N samples of a random eld/vector dened in the currently
selected INPUT module using the default sampling method. If not set otherwise by the user,
the default sampling method used to generate the
i
s variables is 'MC' (Monte Carlo). The
user can call the function uq_setDefaultSampling (described in the UQLAB User Manual
the INPUT module) to change the default sampling method.
X = uq_getSample(myInput,N) returns N samples of the random eld/vector dened in
the INPUT object myInput using the default sampling method.
UQLAB-V2.0-119 - 31 -
UQLAB user manual
X = uq_getSample( myInput,N,method) returns N samples of a random eld/vector de-
ned in the currently selected INPUT object using the sampling method dened in method.
This is a string that can take one of the following values: 3
Table 9: method option of uq_getSample
'MC' Monte Carlo
'LHS' Latin Hypercube
'Sobol' Sobol series
'Halton' Halton series
X = uq_getSample( myInput,N,method, Name, Value) allows for specication of addi-
tional Name - Value pairs of options. The supported options are listed in Table 10.

Name Value Description
method = 'LHS'

default: 5

an attempt to improve the

lhsdesign.

output of uq_getSample may be different when the default or selected INPUT
object is not a random eld.

3.2.1 Printing information: uq_print
Syntax
uq_print(myRF);
UQLAB-V2.0-119 - 32 -
Random elds
Description
uq_print(myRF); prints a report about the INPUT object myRF (Discretization scheme,
correlation function, expansion order, variance error and explained variance).
3.2.2 Graphical visualization: uq_display
Syntax
uq_display(myRF);
Description
uq_display(myRF) produces one or three plots:
Five or one realizations of the random eld for problems of dimension 1 and 2
respectively (for higher dimensional problem, this plot is not produced).
The variance error as computed over the discretization mesh (for higher dimen-
sional problem, this plot is not produced).
The M rst eigenvalues of the spectral decomposition of the correlation matrix.
